brands.description: Google Search, commonly referred to as Google Web Search or Google, is a web search engine owned by Google Inc. It is the most-used search engine on the World Wide Web, handling more than three billion searches each day. As of February 2015 it is the most used search engine in the US with 64.5% market share.
brands.name: Google Search

brands.description: Facebook is an American for-profit corporation and an online social media and social networking service based in Menlo Park, California. The Facebook website was launched on February 4, 2004, by Mark Zuckerberg, along with fellow Harvard College students and roommates, Eduardo Saverin, Andrew McCollum, Dustin Moskovitz, and Chris Hughes.
brands.name: Facebook

brands.description: The first-generation iPad is a tablet computer designed and marketed by Apple Inc. as the first in the iPad line. The device features an Apple A4 processor, a 9.7" touchscreen display, and on certain variants the capability of accessing cellular networks. Using the iOS operating system, the iPad can play music, send and receive email and browse the web.
brands.name: IPad (1st generation)

brands.description: PayPal Holdings, Inc. is an American company operating a worldwide online payments system. Online money transfers serve as electronic alternatives to traditional paper methods like checks and money orders. PayPal is one of the world's largest Internet payment companies.
brands.name: PayPal

brands.description: X.com was an online bank started by Elon Musk in November, 1999 that later became PayPal. It was one of the world's first online banks. Its deposits were insured with FDIC. It had a partnership with Barclays. It was initially funded by Musk and his business mentor Greg Kouri, who went on to fund Musk's later startups Tesla and SpaceX.
brands.name: X.com

brands.description: LinkedIn (/ˌliŋkt.ˈɪn/) is a business- and employment-oriented social networking service that operates via websites and mobile apps. Founded on December 28, 2002, and launched on May 5, 2003, it is mainly used for professional networking, including employers posting jobs and job seekers posting their CVs. As of 2015, most of the company's revenue came from selling access to information about its members to recruiters and sales professionals. As of April 2017, LinkedIn had 500 million members in 200 countries, out of which more than 106 million members are active. LinkedIn allows members (both workers and employers) to create profiles and connections" to each other in an online social network which may represent real-world professional relationships. Members can invite anyone (whether an existing member or not) to become a connection. The "gated-access approach" (where contact with any professional requires either an existing relationship or an introduction through a contact of theirs) is intended to build trust among the service's members. LinkedIn participated in the EU's International Safe Harbor Privacy Principles."
brands.name: LinkedIn

brands.description: Yahoo Inc. (styled as Yahoo!) is an American multinational technology company headquartered in Sunnyvale, California. It is globally known for its Web portal, search engine Yahoo! Search, and related services, including Yahoo! Directory, Yahoo! Mail, Yahoo! News, Yahoo! Finance, Yahoo! Groups, Yahoo! Answers, advertising, online mapping, video sharing, fantasy sports and its social media website.
brands.name: Yahoo!

brands.description: Apple Inc. is an American multinational technology company headquartered in Cupertino, California, that designs, develops, and sells consumer electronics, computer software, and online services. Its hardware products include the iPhone smartphone, the iPad tablet computer, the Mac personal computer, the iPod portable media player, and the Apple Watch smartwatch.
brands.name: Apple Inc.

brands.description: Warby Parker is an American brand of prescription eyeglasses and sunglasses founded in 2010. Warby Parker sells online and has a limited number of showrooms in the United States. The company was founded in 2010 by Neil Blumenthal, Andrew Hunt, David Gilboa, and Jeffrey Raider, and is headquartered in New York City.
brands.name: Warby Parker

brands.description: Google is an American multinational technology company specializing in Internet-related services and products. These include online advertising technologies, search, cloud computing, and software. Most of its profits are derived from AdWords, an online advertising service that places advertising near the list of search results.
brands.name: Google

brands.description: Airbnb is a website for people to list, find, and rent lodging. It has over 1,500,000 listings in 34,000 cities and 190 countries. Founded in August 2008 and headquartered in San Francisco, California, the company is privately owned and operated by Airbnb, Inc.
brands.name: Airbnb

brands.description: Zocdoc is an online medical care scheduling service, providing free of charge medical care search facility for end users by integrating information about medical practices and doctors' individual schedules in a central location.
brands.name: Zocdoc

brands.description: Lyft is a privately held American transportation network company (TNC) based in San Francisco, CA. Launched in June 2012 by Logan Green and John Zimmer, the company's mobile-phone application facilitates peer-to-peer ridesharing by connecting passengers who need a ride with drivers who have a car.
brands.name: Lyft

namedPeople.description: American Engineer who founded PayPal, SpaceX, Tesla Motors and Neuralink. In 2018, his net worth was over $20.8 billion and he was ranked by Forbes as the 53rd richest person in the world.

transcript.text: Welcome to the deep dive.

If you've ever dreamt of, you know, building something totally new, a company, a product, then understanding your market, figuring out where your unique opportunity lies, well, that's absolutely fundamental.
It really is, and today we're digging into some powerful insights specifically on that, drawn from excerpts of Peter Thiel's book Zero to 1.
It's pretty provocative stuff.
Yeah, it definitely challenges the usual playbook.
This isn't about just finding a gap or competing a bit better.
No, not at all.
Thiel argues that real progress, the kind that actually changes things, isn't about copying and improving slightly.
He calls that going from one to north.
Globalization, basically incremental stuff.
Right, just replicating he's focused on creating something brand new that's the zero to 1 leap technology in his broader sense.
Exactly.
And our mission here really for you listening, especially if you're mulling over that startup idea, is to pull out the core methods and, you know, stories from his perspective.
How do you actually find that zero to one spot?
How do you think differently about identifying your market and, importantly, reaching them?
Because, the book argues, startups are kind of uniquely suited for the Zero to 1 creation.
They're nimble.
They can get a small group intensely focused, unlike big corporations maybe.
Or just one person alone.
Right.
But the $1,000,000 question is, how do you spot what needs building if it, well, doesn't exist yet?
And then then how do you connect it to people?
That's what we need to unpack.
OK, let's get into it.
Teal kicks off at this really challenging question.
Apparently uses it in interviews.
What important truth do very few people agree with you on?
And what's so interesting there is how it immediately flips market research on its head.
You're not looking for consensus.
You're not, you know, polling people about needs they already know they have.
You're hunting for a hidden insight, something about how the world works or what people really want that's unpopular or just unseen.
And he makes a good point about why it's hard.
School trains us to repeat what's agreed upon, right?
Saying something true but unpopular.
That takes courage, he thinks.
Courage is rarer than genius, actually.
So applying that to your potential startup, the question becomes something like what valuable company is nobody building?
It forces you to look past the existing landscape.
To imagine a market that should be there.
Exactly.
But then there's this crucial twist, so important for anyone starting out.
It's not just about creating value.
Yes, the airline example.
Right, airlines create huge value moving millions of people, but their profit margins often terrible.
Then you look at Google in a year he cites maybe less total value created in some abstract sense, but they captured a massive chunk as profit.
And Google's value now just dwarfs all the US airlines combined.
So what that tells you as a founder looking for a market is it's not enough to find a need.
You have to find a need within a structure, a market structure where you can actually capture some of that value you create otherwise.
Otherwise, you don't have a business, no matter how useful your product is.
Which leads right into his next point, which feels totally backward at first.
Actively avoid competition.
Yeah, this is a big one.
Business schools teach you to analyze competitors, fight for market share.
Standard stuff.
But Teal says competition is, well, fundamentally destructive.
He uses that Shakespeare analogy.
The Montagues and Capulets fight because they're basically the same.
Companies locked in competition get obsessed with their rivals.
They lose sight of what actually matters, like the customer or the product itself.
You see it all the time, Microsoft versus Google in the browser wars, just copying features back and forth.
Exactly.
That kind of imitative competition leads to these foolish battles over often really minor differences.
rememberthe.com bubblethepets.com wars.
Oh yeah, companies bringing cash trying to destroy rivals.
Selling pet food online without maybe stopping to ask if selling pet food online was even a great business model back then.
Winning the battle meant nothing if everyone lost the war.
He tells that story about PayPal and Elon Musk's x.com too Fierce rivals, practically identical products, offices blocks apart total.
Dogfight, but then the tech bubble starts bursting and they realize the real threat isn't each other, it's the whole market collapsing.
Merging was the only rational move to survive.
So the take away for your market research might be instead of asking how do I compete here, maybe ask is this market just defined by brutal competition?
Right, because if it is, maybe that's not a sign of opportunity.
Maybe it's a sign, as Teal puts it, of a collective hallucination where profits are competed away.
Competition is something to escape, not embrace.
OK, so escape competition towards what?
The goal is building a monopoly, but he means like the good kind.
Yeah, and this definitely needs clarification, because monopoly usually sounds bad.
He defines it simply as a company that's so good at what it does, there's no close substitute.
Google search is his prime example.
For years they just had a vastly better product.
That's the monopoly he means, not an illegal bully.
Exactly, and his argument for why this kind is good.
Unlike companies in perfect competition just scraping by, these monopolists have breathing room.
They can afford to think long term.
They can invest in R&D, yeah, treat employees well, improve the product, even consider their wider impact.
Money isn't the only thing.
Right.
It enables other goals.
And crucially, the value of a business like this isn't just today's profit, it's all the cash flow it's expected to generate way out into the future.
That future value discounted back is the real number.
Which explains why so many tech companies look like they're losing money early on or have these seemingly crazy valuations.
It's not about now, it's about the potential for those durable future monopoly profits maybe 10-15 years out.
Yeah, he uses PayPal, LinkedIn as examples where the valuation was based on that expected durability, not just current growth.
OK, so how do you build that and enduring good monopoly?
He lays out four key characteristics.
If you think about your idea, these are worth asking.
First, proprietary technology.
Your tech has to be genuinely significantly better.
Like 10 times better than the next best thing, not just a slight improvement.
So Google search algorithms back then, maybe Amazon's early logistics tech, the first iPad compared to what came before, stuff that's hard to copy.
Exactly.
Hard to replicate second network effects.
The product gets more valuable as more people use it.
Facebook is the classic.
But he stresses you have to start small to get this going.
Paradoxically small, right?
Like Harvard initially for Facebook you need density in a niche.
Precisely dominate a small pond first.
Third economies of scale.
The business itself should get stronger as it gets bigger.
Fixed costs get spread out.
Software is great for this near 0 cost to add another user.
Makes sense.
And the fourth.
Branding.
But, and this is key, build the substance first, then build the brand around that actual value.
A strong brand reinforces the monopoly, sure, but branding alone, without the substance, it's empty.
He contrasts Yahoo trying to be cool versus Apple building amazing products and letting the brand follow that right.
Build it, then brand it.
So applying this to finding your market, it really reinforces that idea of starting small and scaling intelligently.
Totally.
Don't wade into a giant bloody competitive a devotion.
Find a small niche, a specific group of customers you can completely dominate, then expand outwards from that stronghold.
Like Amazon going from books to CD's to videos outwards.
Their name even hinted at that scale eventually.
Exactly.
Create your own market where you're the leader.
Don't just fight for scraps in someone else's.
OK, another angle on finding opportunity he talks about is looking for secrets.
This connects back to that unpopular truth idea.
Yeah, secrets are important truths that few people see or agree on.
They might be hidden just because they're overlooked, or sometimes because they're kind of forbidden or taboo to talk about.
He argues great companies are often built on these secrets, hiding in plain sight things about how the world works or what people really want.
Think about Airbnb or Uber.
Lyft before they existed.
It seems obvious now, but back then hotels cost a lot, yet tons of spare rooms sat empty.
People needed rides.
Tons of cars sat idle.
They saw that mismatch, untapped supply, unmet demand that Convention just didn't see.
Because people were stuck in the old ways of thinking about hotels and taxis.
He also mentions looking for human secrets, asking what are people not really allowed to talk about.
Like his idea that competition and capitalism are kind of opposites.
Monopolists pretend they aren't dominant.
Competitive firms pretend they're unique.
That's an insight into behavior.
Yeah.
So finding these secrets is like It's unconventional market research, looking beyond the obvious data, asking weird questions, challenging assumptions about your customers or the market itself.
OK, so you found your secret, your insight, you built this unique thing, now you got to get it to people distribution.
He really hammers this .0.
Absolutely, He basically says the engineer's dream, build a great product and they will come is a lie.
Flat out sales matters just as much as product.
That's a big statement.
It is, but his point is a brilliant invention with no way to sell it.
That's just a bad business.
Distribution isn't something you tack on later.
It has to be baked into your thinking from the start part of your market strategy.
And he says distribution follows a power law too, meaning one method will likely be way more effective for your business than all the others combined.
Right.
So that kitchen sink approach, trying a bit of advertising, a bit of sales, a bit of partnerships, it usually fails because you don't master anything, you dilute your effort.
And this is critical for founders planning market entry, he claims.
Most businesses fail because of poor sales.
Not a bad product.
It's a sobering thought.
If you can figure out and master one key distribution channel that works for you, you've got a shot at a great business.
If you try a bunch and none really take off, you're probably done.
So understanding the different types matters.
He breaks it down roughly by deal size, right?
Yeah, there's complex sales for the huge deals, millions of dollars.
Think SpaceX selling to NASA takes intense personal effort over a long time.
Then personal sales maybe in the 10K to 100 dock, a range managed by a sales team.
Relationship building like box selling, cloud storage.
Maybe starting small in one department and expanding.
Sometimes the product helps, like Zocdoc.
More doctors makes it better for other doctors to join.
Got it.
And then for cheaper stuff.
Marketing and advertising for low priced mass market products where you need really low customer acquisition costs.
Detergent glasses like Warby Parker, you need a big megaphone.
But he warns startups don't try to outspend big companies on ads early on.
Right, wait until you have those monopoly profits.
Maybe he mentions that failed PayPal ad versus Priceline using William Shatner after they were big.
Exactly.
So that power law thing means you need to figure out is it complex sales for US, personal sales, marketing, maybe viral growth, though he doesn't detail the how to.
They're much beyond mentioning Paypal's referral program.
You got to find your one channel and own it.
That's market execution.
It's not just the idea, it's getting it out there makes sense, OK.
Beyond product and distribution, he also really stresses getting the foundations right.
Early decisions.
Huge emphasis on this bad calls early on, especially about people almost impossible to fix later.
Choosing a Co founder, he says it's like getting married and founder conflict lethal, an autoimmune disease for the startup.
Yeah you need great people sure, but also structure alignment for the long haul.
Can't just rely on everyone being nice.
He even mentions keeping early CEO salaries relatively low, like under 150K for VC backed ones.
Sets a standard, focuses everyone on building future value sites.
Aaron Levy at Box Living super frugally early on.
And equity becomes key then, orienting people to create that future value.
It's tricky to allocate, but essential to attract people who are truly committed long term.
In culture, it's not about ping pong tables.
No, it's about the team being on a shared mission.
A tribe almost hire people who are talented, yes, but also who genuinely seem to like working together on that specific mission.

You could dress the PayPal mafia camaraderie with maybe thinner relationships at at say a big law firm and defining roles clearly one unique responsibility per person helps minimize that internal conflict, which just drains energy.
The team should be, as he puts it, different in the same way, united by the mission.
Like the early Silicon Valley hoodie uniform signaling you were part of that tribe.
It really grounds it.
Building a company is deeply human right from day one.
Who you choose, how you structure things.
And that leads to a final big idea, controlling your destiny being definite, not indefinite, about the future.
Explain that difference, definite versus indefinite.
Well, you can approach the future of believing you can actually plan for it and shape it.
That's definite.
Or you can treat it as basically random, unpredictable.
So you just try to keep options open, diversify.
That's indefinite.
Like how our education system often pushes people towards broad, safe paths.
OK.
And Teal argues for.
Definite optimism.
Believing the future can be better, but only if you actively plan and work to make it so.
Indefinite approaches, even optimistic ones, where you just hope things get better somehow.
They don't work for building something radically new.
Planning is crucial.
He feels planning is undervalued today.
Very much so in a world focused on short term reaction.
A startup, he argues, is maybe the biggest thing you could have definite mastery over.
You're not just playing the lottery.
You are not a lottery ticket.
I like that your success, if it comes, is down to your plan and execution.

And he uses Tesla as a great example of this, A company that was definitely optimistic, planned meticulously, and got a lot right, including understanding secrets and aiming for that durable monopoly.
Their success wasn't just luck, it was hitting those seven key questions he poses.
Technology, timing, monopoly, people, distribution, durability, and secrets.
And that secret for Tesla was pretty insightful, right?
Understanding early on that cleantech wasn't just about being green.
It was also social, even fashion.
Right, they built a brand around high performance cars that made drivers look cool, appealing to people who wanted to seem green but also just wanted an amazing car.
Totally sidestepped the image of earlier electric.

Cars and their distribution, selling direct, creating their own stores, That was a very definite, specific plan to reach their target customer, bypassing traditional dealers, very planned, very deliberate.
OK, so let's try to wrap up this deep dive into Zero to 1.
For anyone listening who's thinking about that startup journey, it really is a call to rethink how you even look at markets and opportunity.
Absolutely.
It's about hunting for that unique, maybe unpopular truth, escaping the competition trap by building a genuine good monopoly, starting in a niche you can own.
Focusing hard on long term durability through that 10X tech.
Network effects scale real substance behind the brand.
Uncovering secrets about how things really work or what people truly desire.
Mastering that one critical distribution channel.
Getting the foundations, the people, the structure, the culture right from the very beginning.
And crucially, having that definite plan, believing you can shape the future, not just react to it not being a lottery ticket.
Yeah, the book fundamentally challenges you to look past the conventional wisdom, question everything, find value where others don't see it.
It's really arguing against treating the future as random chance.
So.
Thinking about all that, the unpopular truths, the secrets, a staping competition building something definite, maybe the question to leave you with is this.

In a world saturated with information, with so many people chasing the same things, copying each other, what specific unpopular truth about your otential market or your customers are you willing to bet on and build upon, even if maybe esecially if everyone else thinks it sounds kind of crazy?
